(58, 1, '2023-03-26 13:08:55', '2023-03-26 13:08:55', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nehru quickly approached industrialist Jehangir Ratanji Dadabhoy Tata for a solution and Lakm was introduced as Indias first homegrown cosmetics brand in 1952. It was a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tatacentralarchives.com/tata-legacy/lakmes-history.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">subsidiary</a>&nbsp;of Tata Oil Mills, a company originally tasked with crushing copra for exporting coconut oil.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The name Lakme is a French word for goddess Lakshmi, known for her beauty in mythology. This was suggested by the brands French collaborators, Robert Piguet and Renoir. Lakme was a popular opera in France by Lo Delibes, named after its protagonist who was inspired by the Indian goddess.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lakme was groundbreaking for the Indian market because it offered cosmetics suitable for Indian skin types, for which extensive research was&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/349463522_A_Comprehensive_Analysis_of_Top_Indian_Cosmetic_Company_LAKME\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">carried out</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The brand got a<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://corporatecitizen.in/v2-issue3/corporate-history-lakme-was-nehrus-idea.html\" target=\"_blank\">makeover</a>when Dadabhoys Swiss wife Simone Tata took over as its managing director in 1961. From pricing of products to the brands positioning, she made it a household name. Simone became the companys chairperson in 1982.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":42,\"width\":320,\"height\":320,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost/wordpress1/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-from-2023-03-26-18-03-11.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-42\" width=\"320\" height=\"320\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Go-to brand</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I never knew Lakm was an Indian brand. I always thought it was European. And it was affordable too, so I always liked to buy them during my college days. But the reason for my preference was also because it was everywhere. It was advertised in the newspapers, TV and all my favorite actors were in it. I still use some of its products, said 44-year old Seema Rana, a teacher at a Delhi school.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dolly Sharma, also a Delhi resident, had similar reasons for liking Lakm products over others.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My husband runs a pharmacy. Lakm brings us the most revenue because it is the preferred choice of customers. Personally, I have known about the brand for the longest time. It was the only makeup brand I knew that was used by people around memy mother and elder sister. So when it came for my time to choose a brand for myself, it was quite straightforward and simple, she said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '15-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-03-26 13:08:55', '2023-03-26 13:08:55', '', 15, 'http://localhost/wordpress1/wordpress/?p=58', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
